item.title: Man accused of Qld deaths caught in Sydney
item.description: A man who allegedly fled to Sydney after killing a Brisbane couple has been charged with two counts of murder.

item.title: UK-flagged tanker repulses ‘pirate attack’
item.description: Armed pirates have attacked a British-flagged chemical tanker in the Gulf of Aden but were repulsed, the ship's manager Stolt Tankers says.

item.title: Emirates to cut about 30,000 jobs: report
item.description: Emirates Group is planning to cut about 30,000 jobs to reduce costs amid the coronavirus outbreak, which will bring down its number of employees by about 30 per cent from more than 105,000 at the end of March, Bloomberg News reports.

item.title: UK daily virus death toll increases by 170
item.description: The number of people who have died in the United Kingdom after testing positive for COVID-19 has risen by 170 to 34,636, business minister Alok Sharma says, the lowest increase in the official death toll since March 24.

item.title: India extends lockdown, eases measures
item.description: India has extended its nearly two-month-old lockdown by two weeks after reporting nearly 5000 new coronavirus cases but says restrictions could be eased in low-risk areas to boost economic activity.

item.title: Greens economy plan driven by jobs, debt
item.description: Imagine a post-coronavirus world where you commute to work at your government-backed job on an Australian-made bus powered by renewable electricity.

item.title: Tasmanians dine out as virus rules ease
item.description: Tasmanians can eat at restaurants and cafes again as coronavirus restrictions ease in the island state.

item.title: NDIS a bad experience for workers: survey
item.description: Four out of five disability workers say the National Disability Insurance Scheme has been a negative experience for them, a survey reveals.

item.title: Italy death toll lowest since March 9
item.description: The daily death toll from the COVID-19 epidemic in Italy has fallen to 145 - the lowest since March 9 - against 153 the day before, the Civil Protection Agency says.

item.title: Nation rejoices in freedom after lockdown
item.description: Australia has now tested more than one million people for COVID-19 as few new cases were recorded and restrictions were eased across the country.
